          <source>Design for efficiency and operations</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="104" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.pillars-of-a-great-azure-architecture.6-design-for-efficiency-and-operations">
          <source>Check your knowledge</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="105" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.pillars-of-a-great-azure-architecture.6-design-for-efficiency-and-operations">
          <source>Suppose you have recently moved your application to the cloud and your monthly bill seems higher than expected.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="106" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.pillars-of-a-great-azure-architecture.6-design-for-efficiency-and-operations">
          <source>The utilization level of your VM is high enough that you are hesitant to downsize.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="107" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.pillars-of-a-great-azure-architecture.6-design-for-efficiency-and-operations">
          <source>What might be a reasonable next step you could take to help you find inefficiencies?</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="108" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.pillars-of-a-great-azure-architecture.6-design-for-efficiency-and-operations">
          <source>Wait a month and recheck your bill</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="109" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.pillars-of-a-great-azure-architecture.6-design-for-efficiency-and-operations">
          <source>This will tell you where you are spending money but will not help you determine the efficiency level of the components of your system.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="110" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.pillars-of-a-great-azure-architecture.6-design-for-efficiency-and-operations">
          <source>Increase the amount of application testing you do before each release</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="111" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.pillars-of-a-great-azure-architecture.6-design-for-efficiency-and-operations">
          <source>This can improve the quality of your application, but generally would not help you identify infrastructure inefficiencies.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="112" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.pillars-of-a-great-azure-architecture.6-design-for-efficiency-and-operations">
          <source>Add monitoring and instrumentation</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="113" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.pillars-of-a-great-azure-architecture.6-design-for-efficiency-and-operations">
          <source>Continuous monitoring will give you the data you need to find cost savings.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="114" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.pillars-of-a-great-azure-architecture.6-design-for-efficiency-and-operations">
          <source>For example, you might find that demand is extremely variable and multiple small VMs with autoscale could cost less than the single large VM you currently use.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="115" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.pillars-of-a-great-azure-architecture.6-design-for-efficiency-and-operations">
          <source>Which of the following is an example of improving operational efficiency?</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="116" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.pillars-of-a-great-azure-architecture.6-design-for-efficiency-and-operations">
          <source>Automating the deployment of infrastructure</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="117" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.pillars-of-a-great-azure-architecture.6-design-for-efficiency-and-operations">
          <source>Automating the deployment of infrastructure is a great example of improving your operational efficiency.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="118" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.pillars-of-a-great-azure-architecture.6-design-for-efficiency-and-operations">
          <source>Moving services from PaaS to IaaS</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="119" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.pillars-of-a-great-azure-architecture.6-design-for-efficiency-and-operations">
          <source>Moving services from PaaS to IaaS is a step backwards in operational efficiency, as PaaS services typically come with reduced operational costs.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="120" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.pillars-of-a-great-azure-architecture.6-design-for-efficiency-and-operations">
          <source>Documenting manual steps for the deployment of infrastructure</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="121" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.pillars-of-a-great-azure-architecture.6-design-for-efficiency-and-operations">
          <source>Documentation is important with any architecture, but operational improvement comes with automating the manual activities as opposed to simply documenting them.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="122" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.pillars-of-a-great-azure-architecture.6-design-for-efficiency-and-operations">
          <source>Maintaining multiple logging systems</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="123" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.pillars-of-a-great-azure-architecture.6-design-for-efficiency-and-operations">
          <source>Maintaining multiple logging systems comes with increased operational overhead and a reduced ability to correlate events and metrics across the logging systems.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="124" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.pillars-of-a-great-azure-architecture.6-design-for-efficiency-and-operations">
          <source>Centralizing on a single login system can improve operational efficiency.</source>
